     1	# `rhei transition`
     2	
     3	Atomically advance a task's state using compare-and-swap semantics. `rhei transition` is the coordination primitive for manual workers and concurrent agents: only the caller whose expected `--from` matches the task's actual current state wins the race, and every transition is validated against the active state machine before any write.
     4	
     5	## Usage
     6	
     7	```bash
     8	rhei transition <RHEI_PLAN> --task <TASK_ID> --from <STATE> --to <STATE>
     9	```
    10	
    11	## Options
    12	
    13	| Flag             | Required | Default | Description                                                                 |
    14	|------------------|----------|---------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
    15	| `--task <ID>`    | Yes      |         | Task identifier (number or name)                                            |
    16	| `--from <STATE>` | Yes      |         | Expected current state (compare-and-swap guard)                             |
    17	| `--to <STATE>`   | Yes      |         | Target state                                                                |
    18	| `--no-callbacks` | No       | false   | Skip execution of `on_leave` / `on_enter` callbacks registered on the edge  |
    19	
    20	State values passed to `--from` and `--to` follow the state-value rendering rules in the [main spec](../rhei.spec.md#2-state-validity): bare for names that match `IDENTIFIER`, backtick-wrapped otherwise.
    21	
    22	## Behavior
    23	
    24	1. Load the state machine and plan (single-file or directory workspace). Validate.
    25	2. Locate the task by id. Fail if it does not exist.
    26	3. Acquire a file lock on the plan file (single-file plan) or on the task file that contains the task (directory workspace).
    27	4. Re-read the task's current state under the lock. If it does not equal `--from`, fail with a compare-and-swap conflict error and print the actual current state.
    28	5. Validate that a declared transition exists from `--from` to `--to` in the active state machine. Reject if the edge is unlisted.
    29	6. Verify that every required `outputs:` artifact declared on the source state exists (see [States Specification — Artifact Contracts](rhei-states.spec.md#artifact-contracts)). Missing outputs abort the transition.
    30	7. Execute the `on_leave` callback on the source state, if any, unless `--no-callbacks` is set.
    31	8. Rewrite the task's `**State:**` line to the new state value (with counted-visit suffix when applicable).
    32	9. Execute the `on_enter` callback on the target state, if any, unless `--no-callbacks` is set.
    33	10. Append a `## <from> → <to>` entry (with no message body) to `runtime/results/<task-id>.md`, creating the directory if needed. This keeps the transition audit trail consistent with entries written by `rhei complete`.
    34	11. Write the task file atomically (temp file + rename) and release the lock.
    35	
    36	`rhei transition` does not add, remove, or modify the `**Assignee:**` line. Assignment and unassignment are owned by `rhei next` and `rhei complete` respectively.
    37	
    38	Counted-visit accounting: if the target state declares a `visits` budget and `--to` is a loop-back re-entry, the runtime increments `metadata.tasks.<id>.stateVisits.<target>` and renders the new visit number in `**State:**` using the `-<n>` suffix. See [Transitions Specification — Counted Loops](rhei-transitions.spec.md#counted-loops).
    39	
    40	## Compare-and-Swap Conflicts
    41	
    42	Two agents that race on the same task both specify the same `--from`. The first call to acquire the lock rewrites the state. The second call re-reads under the lock, sees the actual state no longer matches `--from`, and fails non-zero with:
    43	
    44	```text
    45	Error: Task <ID> is in state '<actual>', not '<from>'.
    46	       Another transition may have preceded this call.
    47	```
    48	
    49	Losers are expected to re-read the plan and either re-select with `rhei next` or retry against the new state.
    50	
    51	## Output
    52	
    53	On success:
    54	
    55	```text
    56	Task <ID> transitioned: '<from>' -> '<to>'
    57	```
    58	
    59	With `--no-callbacks`:
    60	
    61	```text
    62	Task <ID> transitioned: '<from>' -> '<to>' (callbacks skipped)
    63	```
    64	
    65	## Relationship to Other Commands
    66	
    67	| Command            | What it does                                                                    |
    68	|--------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
    69	| `rhei next`        | Claims the next ready task (assigns without transitioning), prints instructions |
    70	| `rhei next --peek` | Read-only: prints the next claimable task without claiming it                   |
    71	| `rhei transition`  | Atomically changes a task's state; appends entry to result file                 |
    72	| `rhei complete`    | Transitions to terminal, appends result entry, links file, unassigns            |
    73	| `rhei reset`       | Returns each task to its resolved profile's `initial` state, removes `runtime/` |
    74	
    75	The typical agent loop is: `next` (claim) → work → `transition` (advance as needed) → `complete` (finish, record result, release).
    76	
    77	## Related Specifications
    78	
    79	- [Plan Language Specification](../rhei.spec.md) — state-value grammar and validation rules
    80	- [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md) — state machine format
    81	- [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) — transition YAML schema, callbacks, and counted-loop accounting
    82	- [Callbacks Specification](rhei-callbacks.spec.md) — `on_leave` / `on_enter` callback examples
    83	- [Next Command](rhei-next.spec.md) — `rhei next` behavioral contract
    84	- [Complete Command](rhei-complete.spec.md) — `rhei complete` behavioral contract

