     1	# `rhei next`
     2	
     3	Select and optionally claim the next eligible task from a plan.
     4	
     5	## Usage
     6	
     7	```bash
     8	rhei next <RHEI_PLAN> [--peek]
     9	```
    10	
    11	## Options
    12	
    13	| Flag     | Required | Default | Description                                            |
    14	|----------|----------|---------|--------------------------------------------------------|
    15	| `--peek` | No       | false   | Print the next claimable task without transitioning it |
    16	
    17	## Default Behavior (Claim Mode)
    18	
    19	Without `--peek`, `rhei next` atomically claims the next claimable task: it assigns the task to the current agent and prints the task instructions. The task's state is **not** advanced — the agent works in the current state and uses `rhei transition` or `rhei complete` to advance when ready. This is the standard entry point for agents beginning work.
    20	
    21	Initial states are not all treated the same: an initial state that declares runnable autonomous work (`program`, `agent`, `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`) is claimed and presented in place; only non-runnable initial states are auto-advanced to their first forward state before printing instructions.
    22	
    23	A task is *claimable* when:
    24	
    25	1. All tasks listed in its `**Prior:**` field are in terminal states (`completed` or `cancelled`).
    26	2. The task has no `**Assignee:**` field (not already claimed by another agent).
    27	3. Its current state is not terminal (`final: true`) and not gating (`gating: true`).
    28	4. All required `inputs` declared on the task's current state exist.
    29	
    30	### Behavior
    31	
    32	1. Load the state machine and plan. Validate.
    33	2. Scan all tasks in plan order. For each task that satisfies dependency,
    34	   assignee, and state eligibility, resolve the current state's required
    35	   `inputs`.
    36	3. If any required input file for the first otherwise-claimable task is
    37	   missing, stop immediately and fail with an explicit missing-artifact error.
    38	   Do not skip ahead to later tasks.
    39	4. Select the first candidate in plan order.
    40	5. Acquire a file lock on the plan file.
    41	6. Re-read and re-validate the task's claimability under the lock, including
    42	   re-checking required `inputs` (guards against concurrent claims and moved
    43	   files).
    44	7. Set `**Assignee:** <current-agent>` on the task, where `<current-agent>` is the agent id resolved for the task's current state via the [agent resolution order](rhei-agents.spec.md) (state `agent:` field → project settings → global settings). When no agent is configured, the assignee is omitted rather than written as a placeholder.
    45	8. Write the task file atomically (temp file + rename), release lock.
    46	9. Resolve template variables in the state's `instructions` and `personality`
    47	   fields (see [Template Variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality)).
    48	10. Print the task id, title, current state, and resolved instructions to stdout.
    49	
    50	If no claimable task exists, print a status summary (see [No Tasks Ready](#no-tasks-ready)).
    51	
    52	### Output (claim mode)
    53	
    54	Template variables in `instructions` and `personality` are resolved before output. See [Template Variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality) for the full variable namespace and resolution rules.
    55	
    56	```text
    57	Task <ID>: <title>
    58	State: <current-state>
    59	
    60	<resolved instructions from state definition>
    61	```
    62	
    63	### Missing Artifact Error
    64	
    65	If the task that would otherwise be claimed is missing one or more required
    66	input artifacts for its current state, `rhei next` fails and prints an explicit
    67	error instead of silently skipping the task.
    68	
    69	Example:
    70	
    71	```text
    72	Error: Task review-cache-key cannot be claimed in state agent-review-fix.
    73	Missing required input artifact: findings (runtime/findings/review-cache-key.md)
    74	```
    75	
    76	## Peek Mode (`--peek`)
    77	
    78	With `--peek`, `rhei next` performs a read-only scan and prints the next task that *would* be claimed, without modifying the plan or acquiring a lock. This is safe for PM-style navigation, scripting, and inspection.
    79	
    80	Peek mode does **not**:
    81	
    82	- Acquire a file lock
    83	- Modify any state
    84	- Append to result files
    85	- Set or clear `**Assignee:**`
    86	
    87	Peek mode still resolves required `inputs` for the first otherwise-claimable
    88	task. If any are missing, `--peek` fails with the same missing-artifact error as
    89	claim mode.
    90	
    91	### Output (peek mode)
    92	
    93	```text
    94	Next: Task <ID>: <title>
    95	State: <current-state>
    96	```
    97	
    98	If no claimable task exists, the same status summary is printed as in claim mode.
    99	
   100	## No Tasks Ready
   101	
   102	When no claimable task is found, `rhei next` (with or without `--peek`) prints one of three status messages depending on the plan state:
   103	
   104	| Condition                                        | Message                                                                                    |
   105	|--------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
   106	| All tasks in terminal states                     | `Plan complete. All <N> tasks are in terminal states.`                                     |
   107	| One or more tasks in a gating state              | `Blocked: <N> task(s) waiting on human action: Task <ID> (<state>), ...`                   |
   108	| All non-terminal tasks are claimed (in-flight)   | `No tasks available to claim. <N> task(s) are currently in progress: Task <ID> (<state>), ...` |
   109	
   110	These distinct messages allow a PM or orchestrator to tell apart a finished plan, a blocked plan, and a fully in-flight plan. See [States Specification — State Definition](rhei-states.spec.md#per-state-fields) for the `gating: true` field (e.g., `human-review` in the default machine; custom machines may define additional gating states such as `security-review` or `legal-review`).
   111	
   112	## Relationship to Other Commands
   113	
   114	`rhei next` is the claim step of the manual-worker loop: `next` (claim) → work → `transition` (advance as needed) → `complete` (finish, record result, release). `--peek` is the read-only variant that inspects the next claimable task without taking it.
   115	
   116	See [How Rhei Is Used — Command Surface](rhei-usage.spec.md#command-surface) for the full table comparing all five coordination commands.
   117	
   118	## Agent Context
   119	
   120	When a state declares an `agent` field (or an agent is resolved from project/global settings), `rhei next` includes the agent identifier in its JSON output:
   121	
   122	```json
   123	{
   124	  "task_id": "3",
   125	  "title": "Implement caching layer",
   126	  "state": "pending",
   127	  "agent": "claude-code",
   128	  "model": "impl-fast",
   129	  "model_provider": "anthropic",
   130	  "model_name": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
   131	  "instructions": "..."
   132	}
   133	```
   134	
   135	The `agent`, `model`, `model_provider`, and `model_name` fields are omitted
   136	from JSON output when no agent or model is configured.
   137	
   138	In text output mode, the agent is shown after the state line:
   139	
   140	```text
   141	Task 3: Implement caching layer
   142	State: pending
   143	Agent: claude-code (impl-fast = anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6)
   144	
   145	<resolved instructions>
   146	```
   147	
   148	## Related Specifications
   149	
   150	- [Plan Language Specification](../rhei.spec.md) — grammar and semantic constraints
   151	- [How Rhei Is Used](rhei-usage.spec.md) — roles and coordination patterns
   152	- [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md) — state machine format
   153	- [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md) — agent configuration, invocation, and timeout
   154	- [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) — state transition system
   155	- [Transition Command](rhei-transition-cmd.spec.md) — `rhei transition` behavioral contract
   156	- [Complete Command](rhei-complete.spec.md) — `rhei complete` behavioral contract
   157	- [Run Command](rhei-run.spec.md) — `rhei run` behavioral contract
   158	- [Reset Command](rhei-reset.spec.md) — `rhei reset` behavioral contract

