   344	## Template Variables in Instructions and Personality
   345	
   346	The `instructions` and `personality` fields support template variable substitution. Variables use the same `{variable}` syntax as artifact path templates. `rhei next` resolves all template variables before printing output, so agents receive fully expanded prompts with no manual variable resolution required.
   347	
   348	### Variable Namespace
   349	
   350	| Variable | Source | Description | Example Value |
   351	|----------|--------|-------------|---------------|
   352	| `{task_id}` | claimed task | Task identifier as rendered in the plan | `3`, `setup` |
   353	| `{task_title}` | claimed task | Task title text | `Implement caching layer` |
   354	| `{state}` | state machine | Canonical unsuffixed state name | `review` |
   355	| `{visit_count}` | runtime counter | Current visit number for counted-loop states | `2` |
   356	| `{visits}` | state definition | Configured loop budget for the state | `3` |
   357	| `{target}` | target selector | Current execution target selector (requires `target` or `all_targets`) | `codex[yolo]:openai:gpt-5-codex` |
   358	| `{target.slug}` | target selector | Filesystem-safe slug derived from the current target selector | `codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5-codex` |
   359	| `{model}` | model selector | Current model identifier (requires `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`) | `impl-fast` |
   360	| `{model.provider}` | model selector | Resolved provider id for the current model profile | `anthropic` |
   361	| `{model.name}` | model selector | Resolved provider model name for the current model profile | `claude-sonnet-4-6` |
   362	| `{agent}` | agent selector | Current agent identifier (requires `target`, `all_targets`, `agent`, or settings) | `claude-code` |
   363	| `{agent.mode}` | agent selector | Current agent mode, if one was selected | `yolo` |
   364	| `{plan_title}` | plan header | Title from the `# Rhei: <title>` header | `Feature Branch CI Pipeline` |
   365	| `{plan_path}` | filesystem | Path to the plan file | `./ci-pipeline.rhei.md` |
   366	| `{input.<name>.path}` | artifact contract | Resolved path of a declared input artifact | `runtime/results/3.md` |
   367	| `{input.<name>.exists}` | artifact contract | Whether the input artifact file exists on disk at resolution time | `true`, `false` |
   368	| `{output.<name>.path}` | artifact contract | Resolved path of a declared output artifact | `runtime/findings/3.md` |
   369	| `{mcp.<name>.available}` | tooling | Whether the MCP server with id `<name>` started successfully and is attached to the current agent | `true`, `false` |
   370	| `{skill.<id>.available}` | tooling | Whether the skill with id `<id>` is enabled for the current agent | `true`, `false` |
   371	| `{meta.<key>}` | task metadata | Value from the task's YAML metadata section | `alice`, `2` |
   372	
   373	### Resolution Rules
   374	
   375	- **Resolve at output time, not load time.** Template variables are expanded by `rhei next` when printing instructions to an agent. The state machine YAML remains portable — the same `states.yaml` works across different plans.
   376	- **Fail-open on unknown variables.** An unrecognized variable like `{foo}` is left verbatim in the output. This avoids breaking existing instructions that happen to contain braces and makes templates forward-compatible with future variables.
   377	- **Pure substitution, no expressions.** Templates produce text, not decisions. Conditional logic belongs in transition `condition` fields, not in instructions. The resolved text tells the agent "you are on pass 2 of 3" — the agent reads that to decide what to do.
   378	- **Artifact references create a single source of truth.** Using `{input.<name>.path}` or `{output.<name>.path}` instead of repeating raw paths means the artifact contract defines the path once. If the path changes, instructions stay correct automatically.
   379	- **`{visit_count}` and `{visits}` are only meaningful for counted-loop states.** For states without a `visits` declaration, `{visits}` is left unresolved and `{visit_count}` resolves to `1`.
   380	- **`{target}` and `{target.slug}` are only available for target-based execution.** For states that use the legacy `model` / `all_models` fields, `{target}` is left unresolved.
   381	- **Conditional blocks suppress whole paragraphs.** Use `{if input.<name>.exists}`, `{if mcp.<name>.available}`, or `{if skill.<id>.available}` … `{endif}` to include a block of text only when the referenced artifact, server, or skill is present. Use `{else}` between the opening tag and `{endif}` for an alternative block. The entire block — including surrounding blank lines — is removed from the output when the condition is false. Conditional blocks may not be nested in v1.
   382	
   383	### Example
   384	
   385	```yaml
   386	states:
   387	  review:
   388	    description: Review pass that appends findings to a shared artifact.
   389	    instructions: |
   390	      You are on review pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   391	
   392	      Review the current task output and append one numbered review pass to
   393	      `{output.review-notes.path}`.
   394	
   395	      After each review pass, transition to `fix`.
   396	    visits: 2
   397	    outputs:
   398	      - name: review-notes
   399	        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
   400	
   401	  fix:
   402	    description: Fix step that consumes the review artifact.
   403	    instructions: |
   404	      Fix pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   405	
   406	      Read `{input.review-notes.path}`, extract the accumulated review
   407	      findings, and update `{output.fix-notes.path}`.
   408	
   409	      If there is another review pass remaining (you are in pass
   410	      {visit_count} of {visits}), transition back to `review`. Once every
   411	      review-fix cycle is complete, transition to `completed`.
   412	    visits: 2
   413	    inputs:
   414	      - name: review-notes
   415	        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
   416	    outputs:
   417	      - name: fix-notes
   418	        path: runtime/fixes/task-{task_id}-fix-{visit_count}.md
   419	```
   420	
   421	When `rhei next` claims Task 3 ("Implement caching layer") during the second visit to `fix`, the agent receives:
   422	
   423	```text
   424	Fix pass 2 of 2 for Task 3: Implement caching layer.
   425	
   426	Read `runtime/reviews/task-3-review-2.md`, extract the accumulated review
   427	findings, and update `runtime/fixes/task-3-fix-2.md`.
   428	
   429	Transition back to `review` if 2 < 2.
   430	Otherwise, transition to `completed`.
   431	```
   432	
   433	### Multi-Target Example
   434	
   435	```yaml
   436	states:
   437	  review:
   438	    description: Independent review by each target
   439	    personality: |
   440	      You are reviewing as {agent} in mode {agent.mode} for target {target}.
   441	      Provide a review from your perspective.
   442	      Do not attempt to emulate or defer to another target's style.
   443	    instructions: |
   444	      Review the implementation for Task {task_id}.
   445	      Read `{input.implementation.path}` and write your findings to
   446	      `{output.findings.path}`.
   447	    all_targets:
   448	      - claude-code[yolo]:anthropic:claude-opus-4-7
   449	      - gemini[yolo]:google:gemini-3.1-pro-preview
   450	      - codex[yolo]:openai:gpt-5-codex
   451	    inputs:
   452	      - name: implementation
   453	        path: runtime/results/{task_id}.md
   454	    outputs:
   455	      - name: findings
   456	        path: runtime/findings/{task_id}-{target.slug}.md
   457	```
   458	
   459	Here `{target}` and `{target.slug}` appear in both the instructions and the
   460	artifact path. The artifact contract defines the per-target output path once;
   461	instructions reference it by name.
   462	
   463	Recommended authoring pattern for heterogeneous multi-target runs:
   464	
   465	- Declare one shared state with `all_targets` instead of cloning one state per
   466	  target.
   467	- Use `{target.slug}` in output artifact paths so each execution writes to a
   468	  distinct file, for example `runtime/findings/{task_id}-{target.slug}.md`.
   469	- Prefer the full selector form `<agent>[<mode>]:<provider>:<model>` when the
   470	  workflow depends on all four dimensions. Shorter forms are valid when some
   471	  dimensions are intentionally omitted.
   472	- Add a later synthesis state that consumes the per-target artifacts and writes
   473	  one final document.
   474	
   475	## Agent Field
   476	
   477	States can declare which coding agent transport executes work in that state. The
   478	`agent` field is always a string id. Rhei resolves the id against the merged
   479	`agents` registry — the built-in agents (`claude-code`, `codex`, `gemini`,
   480	`kilocode`, `cursor`) plus any entries declared in
   481	`~/.config/rhei/settings.json` and `<plan-root>/.rhei/settings.json`. Inline
   482	object-shaped agent definitions are not accepted on a state; a custom agent
   483	must be declared in the registry first.
   484	
   485	The optional `agent_mode` field selects a named flag set from the resolved
   486	agent's `modes` map. See [Agents Specification — Modes](rhei-agents.spec.md#modes)
   487	for the common `yolo` / `safe` conventions and the full mode resolution order.
   488	
   489	```yaml
   490	states:
   491	  draft:
   492	    description: Task requires analysis before execution.
   493	    model: impl-deep
   494	    agent: claude-code
   495	    agent_timeout: 15m
   496	
   497	  pending:
   498	    description: Task is ready for implementation.
   499	    model: impl-fast
   500	    agent: claude-code
   501	    agent_mode: yolo
   502	    agent_timeout: 30m
   503	
   504	  agent-review:
   505	    description: A separate reviewing agent inspects the result.
   506	    model: review-deep
   507	    agent: codex
   508	    agent_mode: safe
   509	    agent_timeout: 20m
   510	
   511	  agent-review-fix:
   512	    description: The implementing agent addresses reviewer findings.
   513	    model: impl-fast
   514	    agent: claude-code
   515	    agent_timeout: 30m
   516	
   517	  human-review:
   518	    gating: true
   519	    # No agent - humans act here
   520	
   521	  completed:
   522	    final: true
   523	  cancelled:
   524	    final: true
   525	```
   526	
   527	When `agent` is set on a state, `rhei run` spawns that agent transport to
   528	execute work. When `agent` is omitted, `rhei run` falls back to project-level
   529	or global-level `defaults.agent`. See
   530	[Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md) for full resolution order,
   531	invocation profiles, modes, and timeout handling.
   532	
   533	The `model` field names a model profile, which resolves to a provider/model
   534	combo in settings. The `agent` field is an optional transport for autonomous
   535	execution. Either can be set independently at any configuration level, and the
   536	resolution merges across levels.
   537	
   538	## Program States
   539	
   540	States can declare a deterministic program to execute instead of spawning an AI agent. The `program` field names a command (string form) or provides a structured command definition (object form). Program states are the right choice for build, test, lint, deploy, and other steps where the behavior is fixed and an AI agent adds no value.
   541	
   542	```yaml
   543	states:
   544	  build:
   545	    description: Build the project
   546	    program: "make build"
   547	    program_timeout: 10m
   548	
   549	  test:
   550	    description: Run the test suite
   551	    program:
   552	      command: ["npm", "test", "--", "--coverage"]
   553	      env:
   554	        NODE_ENV: test
   555	    program_timeout: 15m
   556	    outputs:
   557	      - name: coverage
   558	        path: coverage/lcov.info
   559	
   560	  deploy:
   561	    description: Deploy to staging
   562	    program:
   563	      command: ["./scripts/deploy.sh", "{meta.deploy_env}"]
   564	      working_directory: ./infra
   565	    program_timeout: 20m
   566	```
   567	
   568	When `program` is set, `rhei run` spawns the command as a subprocess instead of an agent. The program communicates its outcome via exit code, and transitions from program states can declare `exit_code` conditions for automatic routing:
   569	
   570	```yaml
   571	transitions:
   572	  - from: build
   573	    to: test
   574	    exit_code: 0
   575	  - from: build
   576	    to: failed
   577	    exit_code: nonzero
   578	```
   579	
   580	A state must not declare both `agent` and `program` — they are mutually exclusive. The `program` field is also incompatible with `gating: true` (programs run autonomously).
   581	
   582	See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md) for the complete specification including program declaration forms, exit-code transitions, environment variables, timeout handling, and validation rules.
   583	
   584	## MCP Servers and Skills
   585	
   586	States can attach **MCP servers** and **skills** to the agent subprocess. MCP
   587	servers expose tools through the Model Context Protocol; skills bundle
   588	agent-side prompts and resources. Both are tooling that shapes what an agent
   589	can do in a given phase — research, implementation, review, and so on.
   590	
   591	The `mcp_servers` and `skills` fields are lists. Each entry is either a
   592	**registry id** (a string naming an entry in the merged
   593	[`mcp_servers`](rhei-agents.spec.md#mcp_servers) or
   594	[`skills`](rhei-agents.spec.md#skills) settings registry) or an **inline
   595	object** for one-offs that shouldn't pollute global settings.
   596	
   597	### Entry forms
   598	
   599	```yaml
   600	states:
   601	  pending:
   602	    agent: claude-code
   603	    mcp_servers: [postgres]                         # registry id
   604	    skills: [test-authoring]
   605	
   606	  agent-review:
   607	    agent: codex
   608	    mcp_servers:
   609	      - id: postgres                                # registry id (long form)
   610	      - id: grafana
   611	        optional: true                              # warn-and-continue if missing
   612	    skills:
   613	      - id: security-review
   614	      - id: ad-hoc-review                           # inline (no registry entry required)
   615	        path: ./.rhei/skills/ad-hoc-review
   616	        optional: true
   617	```
   618	
   619	The object form accepts `id`, `optional`, and the fields of the corresponding
   620	registry entry (`command`/`url`/`transport`/`env`/... for MCP servers; `path`
   621	and `description` for skills). The string form is shorthand for `{id: <name>}`
   622	with `optional: false`.
   623	
   624	### Effective set
   625	
   626	The **effective set** for a state is `defaults.<kind>` ∪ `state.<kind>`,
   627	deduplicated by id. State-level entries override identically-ided defaults.
   628	Passing `mcp_servers: []` or `skills: []` on a state clears the inherited
   629	`defaults` tooling for that state — leaving the field out inherits the
   630	defaults unchanged. See
   631	[Agents Specification — Resolution Order](rhei-agents.spec.md#resolution-order)
   632	for the full algorithm.
   633	
   634	### Runtime semantics
   635	
   636	- Entries are resolved and availability-checked by `rhei run` at agent spawn
   637	  time — not at `rhei next`.
   638	- Required entries (the default) that fail their availability check block the
   639	  agent spawn. The engine fires an `mcp_unavailable` or `skill_unavailable`
   640	  transition if one is declared from the current state; otherwise the task
   641	  stays in place with an error logged.
   642	- Optional entries (`optional: true`) that fail produce a warning and are
   643	  dropped from the effective set. The agent still spawns with the remaining
   644	  resolved tooling.
   645	- For every declared entry — required or optional — the engine exposes:
   646	  - `{mcp.<name>.available}` / `{skill.<id>.available}` template variables
   647	    resolved to `true` or `false`.
   648	  - `RHEI_MCP_<NAME>_AVAILABLE` / `RHEI_SKILL_<ID>_AVAILABLE` environment
   649	    variables (name uppercased, hyphens and spaces replaced with underscores).
   650	- The aggregate resolved set is also exposed via `RHEI_MCP_SERVERS` and
   651	  `RHEI_SKILLS` as comma-separated id lists containing only the entries that
   652	  started successfully.
   653	
   654	See [Agents Specification — Missing Tooling](rhei-agents.spec.md#missing-tooling)
   655	for availability semantics, timeout behavior, and the
   656	`mcp_unavailable` / `skill_unavailable` transition contract. See
   657	[Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) for declaring those
   658	transitions.
   659	
   660	### Example
   661	
   662	```yaml
   663	states:
   664	  draft:
   665	    description: Research phase — agent needs read access to the issue tracker.
   666	    agent: claude-code
   667	    mcp_servers: [linear]
   668	    instructions: |
   669	      Read Task {task_id}: {task_title} and linked Linear tickets.
   670	
   671	      {if mcp.linear.available}
   672	      Use the Linear MCP to fetch related tickets and comments before writing
   673	      the task description.
   674	      {else}
   675	      Linear is unavailable — rely on the task body only and flag any missing
   676	      context in your description.
   677	      {endif}
   678	
   679	      Transition to `pending` once the description is finalized.
   680	
   681	  pending:
   682	    description: Implementation phase.
   683	    agent: claude-code
   684	    mcp_servers: [postgres]
   685	    skills: [test-authoring]
   686	
   687	  agent-review:
   688	    description: Independent review.
   689	    agent: codex
   690	    mcp_servers:
   691	      - id: postgres
   692	      - id: grafana
   693	        optional: true
   694	    skills: [security-review]
   695	    instructions: |
   696	      Review Task {task_id}.
   697	
   698	      {if mcp.grafana.available}
   699	      Pull relevant latency panels from Grafana for any request-path changes
   700	      and cite them in your findings.
   701	      {else}
   702	      Grafana is unavailable — note the omission in findings but do not block
   703	      the review on it.
   704	      {endif}
   705	```
   706	
   707	## Profiles
   708	
   709	A **profile** is a named bundle of `{initial, allowed}` that defines a
   710	per-node state policy. Profiles are defined once at the top level of the
   711	state machine YAML and referenced from `node_policy`.
   712	
   713	Separating policy from state definitions means:
   714	
   715	- One canonical definition of each state and transition.
   716	- Multiple node kinds can share a profile without duplicating `allowed`
   717	  arrays.
   718	- The root node can use a different profile than task or bug nodes, without
   719	  cloning the state graph.
   720	- `rhei reset` resets each node to its resolved profile's `initial` — there is
   721	  no single machine-wide initial state.
   722	
   723	> The `profiles` block in this spec is distinct from the `models` list of
   724	> *model profiles*. A `models` entry names a model profile identifier
   725	> resolved through settings to a provider/model combination. A `profiles`
   726	> entry is a state policy assigned to nodes. They live at different layers
   727	> of the machine and never resolve against each other.
   728	
   729	### Shape
   730	
   731	```yaml
   732	profiles:
   733	  <profile-name>:
   734	    initial: <state-name>        # starting state for any node using this profile
   735	    allowed: [<state-name>, ...] # states any such node may ever hold
   736	```
   737	
   738	### Per-profile validation
   739	
   740	- `initial` must be defined in `states`.
   741	- Every entry in `allowed` must be defined in `states`.
   742	- `initial` must appear in `allowed`.
   743	- `allowed` must contain at least one state marked `final: true`.
   744	- Every non-final state in `allowed` must have a path — using only
   745	  transitions whose `to` is also in `allowed` — to some final state in
   746	  `allowed`. This reachability check prevents a narrowed `allowed` set from
   747	  silently producing a policy where a node can enter a state it can never
   748	  leave.
   749	
   750	### Example
   751	
   752	```yaml
   753	profiles:
   754	  simple:
   755	    initial: pending
   756	    allowed: [pending, completed, cancelled]
   757	
   758	  reviewed:
   759	    initial: draft
   760	    allowed: [draft, pending, agent-review, agent-review-fix, human-review, completed, cancelled]

